---
import ServiceLayout from '../../layouts/ServiceLayout.astro';

const title = 'Corporate &amp; marketing website development';
const description =
  'Fast, indexable presentation websites for small businesses, agencies, and B2B brands. Design, copy, build, hosting and SEO from one team.';
---

<ServiceLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  serviceType="Corporate website development"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
    { href: '/web', label: 'Websites' },
    { href: '/web/corporate', label: 'Corporate &amp; marketing' },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Most company websites do one of three jobs: convince a visitor to get in touch, convince a
    visitor to buy, or convince a visitor that the company is real and competent. Often all
    three. We build presentation websites that do those jobs honestly — without stock photos
    of handshakes, without buzzword salads, without animations that break on slower phones.
  </p>

  <h2>What we build</h2>
  <p>
    The category covers a lot of shapes. A one-page landing site for a new product. A
    five-to-ten page company website for a small business that needs services, about, blog and
    contact. A twenty-page site for an agency or consultancy with case studies and team bios. A
    fifty-page content hub for a B2B company that uses the site as a sales tool.
  </p>
  <p>
    For all of these we usually pick a static site generator — <strong>Astro</strong>, Next.js
    (static export), Hugo, or Eleventy — paired with a lightweight content management system if
    you want to update copy yourself. Static sites are nearly impossible to break, load
    instantly, work brilliantly on cheap hosting, and get crawled and indexed properly by search
    engines. Unless you have an actual reason to need WordPress (e.g., your team already knows
    it), we don't recommend it for new builds — the maintenance burden is real.
  </p>

  <h2>End-to-end work</h2>

  <h3>Strategy and structure</h3>
  <p>
    Before we draw a single page, we work out who's coming to your site, what they're looking
    for, what the next step is, and what would stop them taking it. The page structure follows
    from that, not from a generic template. Most sites have too many pages — we usually end up
    with fewer than the brief asked for.
  </p>

  <h3>Domain, email and hosting</h3>
  <p>
    We help pick and register your domain, set up email through Google Workspace, Microsoft
    365 or our own mail server, and configure DNS so messages from your domain authenticate
    correctly. For hosting, a small VPS or a CDN-backed static host handles a presentation site
    for the cost of a coffee per month — we'll show you the options.
  </p>

  <h3>Visual design</h3>
  <p>
    We design from a small set of reusable components — type scale, colour palette, button
    styles, card patterns — rather than treating each page as a one-off. That keeps the site
    looking consistent and means changes later (a new section, a new template) take hours
    rather than days. Brand assets you already have, we use; brand assets you don't yet have,
    we help you decide on the minimum needed.
  </p>

  <h3>Copywriting support</h3>
  <p>
    We can edit the copy you've written, write a draft you can refine, or work alongside a
    copywriter you bring. Either way we'll push for plain English over jargon — it ranks better
    in search and converts better in real life. If you don't have copy yet, we'll help you
    work out the structure first so the writing has somewhere to go.
  </p>

  <h3>SEO that actually helps</h3>
  <p>
    Title tags and meta descriptions per page, clean URL structure, sitemap, robots.txt,
    schema.org structured data (Organization, BreadcrumbList, Article where appropriate),
    Open Graph and Twitter Card tags so links shared on social show a proper preview, fast
    load times (Core Web Vitals all green), accessible markup. We don't promise specific
    rankings — anyone who does is lying — but we make sure your site is technically excellent
    so good content has a chance to rank.
  </p>

  <h3>Forms, analytics and integrations</h3>
  <p>
    Contact forms that go straight to your inbox (and a database, so nothing's lost). Analytics
    (Plausible if you want privacy-friendly, GA4 if you want the standard). Newsletter signups
    (MailerLite, ConvertKit, MailChimp). Calendly or Cal.com for booking calls. CRM
    integrations (HubSpot, Pipedrive, Salesforce) if you have a sales pipeline.
  </p>

  <h3>Easy updates afterwards</h3>
  <p>
    If you want to update copy or add blog posts yourself, we wire up a lightweight CMS — usually
    one with a clean editor that doesn't require training. If you'd rather we handle updates,
    that's also fine: most small changes take fifteen minutes and we charge by the hour.
  </p>

  <h2>Performance and accessibility</h2>
  <p>
    Every page we ship aims for a Lighthouse score of 95+ across performance, accessibility,
    best practices, and SEO. We use semantic HTML, proper heading hierarchy, sufficient colour
    contrast, keyboard-navigable forms, and alt text on every image. For most companies this
    is a nice-to-have; for some (especially in the public sector or selling to large
    enterprises), it's required by law or by procurement.
  </p>

  <h2>What it costs</h2>
  <p>
    A clean five-page company site lands between £2,500 and £4,500 depending on how much
    design and copy work you need. A larger site with a blog, case studies and a couple of
    custom landing pages runs £4,500 to £9,000. Hosting and domain run a few pounds a month
    each. We'll quote in writing with a fixed price and timeline, and we won't ask for changes
    to scope without putting them in writing first.
  </p>

  <h2>Timeline</h2>
  <p>
    A small site goes from kickoff to launch in three to five weeks. A larger site or one
    requiring custom illustration or video takes six to ten. We share progress at each step,
    you see staging URLs early, and the launch itself is undramatic — usually a Tuesday
    morning, nothing on fire.
  </p>
</ServiceLayout>
